You use conda info --envs.

26
00:01:59.581 --> 00:02:03.000
And you can see that I have
four environments out there.

27
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.550
Yours will probably have just one,
and that'll be root.

28
00:02:06.550 --> 00:02:09.950
Now we're going to create
other environments.

29
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:18.680
And this is the command that you use
to do that, conda create -n for name.

30
00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:20.790
And then I'm going to create
one called python362,

31
00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:26.850
because I'm going to create
an environment for running Python 3.6.2,

32
00:02:26.850 --> 00:02:32.470
which is a version that I
had when I looked at Spyder.

33
00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:36.743
You've written it down, you can- Do

34
00:02:36.743 --> 00:02:42.210
whatever version your machine has.

35
00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:49.653
Now this name is can be anything,
you can name it whatever you want.

36
00:02:49.653 --> 00:02:54.743
And you put for Python version,
whatever version you got, and Spyder.

37
00:02:57.021 --> 00:03:01.095
Once you've entered that, press return and

38
00:03:01.095 --> 00:03:06.786
it'll start fetching what it
needs to from the web to install.

39
00:03:08.651 --> 00:03:12.228
When it gets through, it'll ask you
whether you want to proceed and

40
00:03:12.228 --> 00:03:12.930
you say yes.

41
00:03:14.210 --> 00:03:20.500
And now it's installing that additional
